@Eric Houghland
Chinese does have TENSE, but there is no conjugation of verbs. For example, if you add "-LE" to the end of a verb, it indicates a completed action, and therefore past tense. Similarly, adding "-ZHE" to a verb indicates a current action, and therefore present tense. But mostly just saying when does the job, as in,  "I tomorrow go store buy shoes."

@Digicate I can't accept homophones.com as an authority, beause they also say "sari" and "sorry" are homophones:  <a href="https://www.homophone.com/h/sari-sorry" target="_blank">https://www.homophone.com/h/sari-sorry</a>.
There may be dialects where an apology sounds similar to an article of Indian clothing, but that doesn't make the words homonyms in standard Engkish.

By the way, the site also claims canape/canopy, caster/castor, magnate/magnet, heir/air/err/are, and ho/hoe/whoa are (air?) homophones of each other.

